Given a piece of C# code that generates a recursive function, how can we transform it into an iterative one that still achieves the same result and has a lower time complexity?

```csharp
int Fibonacci(int n)
{
    if (n <= 1)
        return n;
 
    return Fibonacci(n - 1) + Fibonacci(n - 2);
}
```

Assume that the function computes the nth number in the Fibonacci sequence.

output1:
We can transform the recursive function into an iterative one by using a loop that starts from the second number in the sequence (n-1) and iterates up to n, computing each number in the sequence as the sum of the two preceding ones. This approach reduces the time complexity from O(2^n) to O(n), as each number in the sequence is computed only once. Here's the iterative version of the code:

```csharp
int Fibonacci(int n)
{
    int fib = 0, prevFib = 1;
    for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++)
    {
        int temp = fib;
        fib += prevFib;
        prevFib = temp;
    }
    return fib;
}
``` 

In this version, we initialize two variables, fib and prevFib, to 0 and 1 respectively, which are the first two numbers in the sequence. We then use a loop that starts from the third number (i.e., 2) and iterates up to n, computing each number in the sequence as the sum of the two preceding ones, and updating the values of fib and prevFib accordingly. Finally, we return the value of fib, which is the nth number in the sequence.

